1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:06,880
A full football match contains a few moments people need,
buried inside everything else.

2
00:00:07,408 --> 00:00:12,773
Every Angle finds those moments,
then makes a human the final authority.

3
00:00:13,259 --> 00:00:20,363
The system narrows the footage, Claude proposes what happened,
and an editor reviews the evidence.

4
00:00:20,885 --> 00:00:26,654
Only verified events reach this match summary,
search, or the final reel.

5
00:00:27,141 --> 00:00:31,182
The provenance timeline keeps the whole process visible:

6
00:00:31,677 --> 00:00:40,441
candidate windows below, human decisions alongside them,
and every available verified clip playable in place.

7
00:00:40,962 --> 00:00:43,432
Here is the human-in-the-loop step.

8
00:00:43,916 --> 00:00:47,445
The model suggests a goal from the visual sequence.

9
00:00:47,965 --> 00:00:54,411
The editor can inspect the footage, correct the description,
reject it, or keep it.

10
00:00:54,895 --> 00:00:58,302
This decision updates the verified manifest.

11
00:00:58,786 --> 00:01:03,414
Search is grounded in that manifest,
not raw model output.

12
00:01:03,898 --> 00:01:13,382
A natural-language query finds the verified moment where the keeper
comes off his line, with its clip and provenance attached.

13
00:01:13,872 --> 00:01:19,647
Quick Highlights groups replay-adjacent incidents
and selects a deterministic edit.

14
00:01:20,131 --> 00:01:26,904
The organizer can change the order, while FFmpeg assembles the reel
without another model call.

15
00:01:27,396 --> 00:01:40,761
For a club or content team, that turns a long recording into searchable,
ready-to-share moments — while keeping the person, the evidence, and the rights boundary in control.

16
00:01:41,252 --> 00:01:42,241
Every Angle.

17
00:01:42,729 --> 00:01:44,165
Find the moments.

18
00:01:44,694 --> 00:01:45,957
Prove every one.
